div.div:
Editor Library
Classes / GUI widgets / windows to view and modify LibrePCB data structures
- Provides the undo stack framework and commands to modify libraries and projects
- Contains all the editor logic (state machines etc.)
- Error handling: Catch exceptions thrown in static libraries and show them visually
- Requires a window manager

div.div:
C++ Core Library
- Contains data structures, algorithms, utils, ...
- Error handling: Exceptions or something like "isValid()"
- No GUI classes / functionality at all!
- No dependency to window manager (i.e. must work headless)
Hierarchy of 4 layers, only allowed to access lower layers:
- L4: workspace (settings, database, ...)
- L3: project (schematic, board, drc, ...)
- L2: library (symbol, package, component, ...)
- L1: common (core data structures, algorithms, utils, ...)

div.div:
Rust Core Library
- Thin FFI for modules to be accessed from C++
- No dependency to Qt or window manager
Bottom-up approach to migrate LibrePCB from C++ to Rust,
starting with rather independent low-level functionality.

Some are vendored in the "libs" subdirectory and statically linked, others (e.g. Qt6) need to be installed on the system and are dynamically linked. Some of the vendored libraries can optionally also be unbundled.
